          "body": "Some Pharisees — perhaps friendly, perhaps maneuvering — warn Jesus that Herod wants to kill Him. Jesus's reply is the most politically defiant sentence in the Gospels. *Go and tell that fox* — naming Antipas with the contempt due a predator pretending to be sovereign — *I cast out demons and perform cures today and tomorrow, and the third day I reach My goal*. The threefold *today, tomorrow, third day* is not literal calendar but Hebraic idiom for *a short, fixed period*, and *teleioo* (reach My goal, be perfected) deliberately invokes both the completion of His ministry and the completion of His death-and-resurrection. Then the lament: *O Jerusalem, Jerusalem* — the doubled vocative is the prophetic cry. Jesus reveals He has *often* wanted to gather Jerusalem's children — divine-maternal imagery, hen-with-her-brood, an image the OT uses of God Himself (Deuteronomy 32:11; Psalm 17:8; 91:4). *And you would not have it.* The chapter ends with *your house is left to you desolate* — the temple's coming destruction announced in advance — and a calendared promise: *you will not see Me until you say, Blessed is He who comes in the name of the Lord*. Jerusalem's next sight of her Messiah is locked to her own repentant confession of Psalm 118:26."
